ONDERZOEKERS EN ZELFBOUWERS

Het jeugdlab van De Jonge Onderzoekers
Amsterdam is elke zaterdag open van 12-17
uur voor alle jonge mensen met interesse in
electronica, computers, scheikunde, biologie en
dergelijke. Het adres is: Willem Beukelsstraat
42 (vlakbij de Middenweg) Amsterdam
(Watergraafsmeer).

In plaats van de Dag voor de Amateur houdt de
VERON dit jaar een 'Dag voor de Zelfbouw'. Dit
evenement vindt plaats op zaterdag 15 november
in het RAI-Congrescentrum. In feite is de formule
gelijk aan de Dag van de Amateur maar dan zonder
lezingen.

INTERNATIONALE RADIOBOEKEN

Jonathan Marks van de Wereldomroep krijgt
altijd, vanwege het internationale karakter
van zijn programma, tal van reacties en
interessante boeken die niemand anders
onder ogen krijgt. Jonathan is de presentator
en eindredakteur van het programma Media
Network bij de Wereldomroep. Zijn stem is bij
ons te horen als hij de 'Basicode Software
Service' aankondigt. Via de Wereldomroep is
zijn programma over de hele wereld te horen
als het donderdag (driemaal) op verschillende
frekwenties en tijden wordt uitgezonden.
Hij recenseerde de volgende boeken voor zijn
programma en voor ons, uiteraard in zijn
moedertaal.

1 SATELLITE HANDBOOK

A new edition of the satellite handbook,
called Communications Satellites', has been
published in the USA by Grove Enterprises
of Brasstown North Carolina. Its author is
Larry van Horn, who has put together a very
comprehensive 255 page guide to the thousands
of pieces of metal circling above our heads,
and whats more to the point, how you can monitor
the communications going up and coming back
from them. Further information is available
from Grove Enterprises, Box 98, Brasstown,
North Carolina 28902 USA. The price is $15.95
in the USA, 17.95 elsewhere including
surface mail postage.

2 INTERNATIONAL LISTENING

The West German publishers of the International
Listening Guide have announced a new
publication. To be called, the 'International
Broadcasting Handbook', this new annual will
be issued in the second week of December. As
well as station schedules, the new handbook
will include addresses, details of national
holidays, maps showing locations of major
shortwave transmitter sites, broadcasts in
language order, time charts, and so the list
goes on. Special software and printing
arrangements have been made to make the
publication available within 17 days of the
editorial deadline. Pre-publication price is
35 German Marks in Europe, 45 Marks for
Australasia, and 40 Marks anywhere else,
including airmail postage. The quarterly
International Listening Guide, thats been
appearing for the last 8 years, will continue.
The latest edition includes some 48 pages of
station schedules that went into effect
since September 7th. Once you get the hang of
the quite extensive abbreviations, the guide
turns out to be very comprehensive. The data
is in time, frequency, and country order, and
new in the latest edition is a tropical band
survey. Subscriptions to the quarterly guide
vary depending on where you live. A sample
issue costs 5 international reply coupons from
the International Listening Guide,
Merianstrasse 2, D-3588 Homberg,
West Germany.

3 RADIO DATABASE INT.

Just off the press in the United States is
the 1987 edition of Radio Database
International, a 352 page guide to the
broadcasting airwaves between 2260 and 21810
kHz to be exact. This is the second, and
completely revised edition, based on
monitoring reports and station schedules
entered into a large computer database
system. Editor in Chief Larry Magne has
succeeded in getting the system to put out
its data in a very easy to follow form. If
you tune up 6035 kHz, and look up 6035
in the book, you can find out which stations
use that channel, when, where the programme
is aimed, and if it its one of 9 selected
languages categories, you can determine
exactly when the station is running English,
French, German, Spanish, Portuguese, Chinese,
Japanese, Russian or Arabic programmes. Once
you get the hand of the graphic symbols, its
easy to see at a glance what you're listening
too. The information is mostly up-to-date,
including frequencies that many stations will
use as from September 28th. Just how accurately
RDI can predict exactly what Radio Moscow,
the world's largest external broadcaster, will
do in October and November of this year is
something that can only be checked later.
This 1987 edition is bigger than last year,
partly because it incoporates information
previously published in two separate
editions, one for the tropical broadcast bands,
and then everything from 49 to 13 metres. 11
metres, equivalent to 25 MHz isn't included
because that shortwave band isn't working at
present, due to the low sunspot number.
New this year are a number of concise articles
by guest authors, including Graham Mytton of
the BBC Audience research department who
explains how they count their 100 million,
or more recently, 120 million estimated
listeners.

OOK TECHNISCHE TESTS

The final 60 pages of the publication give a
comprehensive, and very readable survey of
the shortwave receiver market. The reviews
keep the technicalities to a minimum, with a
lot of down to earth comments that even
newcomers can understand. RDI is building up
more technical files on the expensive receivers,
so that you can follow up on exact details if
you need them. These are separate publications
though. In summary its well printed, well bound,
and easy to use. There are some negative point
too. If you're used to looking at the clock,
and then looking for a guide to whats on the
radio dial now, RDI won't help you. Its
designed for accessing by frequency or by
country, not by time. Thats a major drawback
for a non technical person who's interested in
something like a world news bulletin not a
casual scan of the bands. For some reason
the table of contents is on pages 18 and 19,
which doesn't make it quick to find unless you
turn down the pages. Whilst the listing of the
clandestine radio services heard on shortwave
is unique, the regularity of some of the hobby
pirates also in the book is questionable. Some
of the captions accompanying the receiver photos
seem to have gone wrong towards the end of
the book. We're told of the New RX-325 from
Ten-Tacs, the hot new HRD-525 from Japan Radio,
and Drakes Vernerable R-7. Mind you no
publication is free of typographical slips, and
the accompanying text does clear up any queries.

GEEN MIDDENGOLF GEGEVENS

The RDI book does not include any medium wave
frequencies used by external broadcasters. Whilst
that isn't relevant to north America, it is for
listeners in Europe, part of Africa and Central
America, and Asia. Often, the medium wave channel
is the only way to hear a certain language
broadcast if shortwave isn't reliable over short
distances due to propagation or interference.
An indication of medium wave channels would be
a welcome addition for the next edition in 12
months time. To conclude, this book will suit
the world band radio listener interested in
identifying what he or she hears. Its lives
up to its reputation, and its reasonably
priced. The cover price is 12 dollars 95 cents
in the US, excluding shipping costs. RDI is
now distributed through appointed agents, and
their prices vary. If you'd like more
information, then the advice is to write to
this address: RDI, Box 300, Penns Park PA
18943 USA.

SONY MSX-2 TIP

Hans van Helden schrijft ons de volgende tip
die hij gebruikt wanneer er onvoldoende
geheugen beschikbaar is op de Sony MSX-2,
bijv. als de Beeldkrant te lang blijkt:
1. Zet het vertaalprogramma op tape, als het
op disk staat. 2. Start de computer terwijl
men herhaaldelijk Shift en Ctrl indrukt.
Hierdoor wordt de geheugenruimte voor het
disksysteem niet aangesproken. 3. De disk
is dus nu niet aanspreekbaar. 4. CLOAD nu
het vertaalprogramma en RUN het. 5. CSAVE
nu het vertaalde programma en zet de computer
uit (Reset) 6. CLOAD nu het te lange programma
van tape en SAVE het op disk. Hans heeft een
HB-500 MSX-2 computer waarmee deze truc werkt.

Ronald Koelink bericht ons nog dat er in
Diemen een speciale MSX Node met succes staat
te draaien. Het telefoonnummer is: 020-982502.

